{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_charleston_ver01/data/sn85025570/0038334699A/1907112701/0407.xml":{"full_text":"-y-\nCatarrh\n\"Whether it is of the nose, throat,\nStomach, bowels, or more delicate or\ngans, catarrh is always debilitating and\nShould have attention.\nThe discharge from the mucous\nmembrane is because this is kept in a\nState of inflammation by an impure\ncondition of the blood. Therefore,\nto\ncure, take the best blood purifier,\nHood's Sarsaparilla\nRedwood Octette\n1 5 0 e Y e a i n A v a n e\nWEDNESDAY, NOV. 27,1907.\nBY JAMES AIKEN\nADVERTISING BATE8,\nLessttian 20 inches (1 col.) per inch.... 20c.\nTwenty incnes or more, per inch J.&C.\nDiscounts will be allowed on\nI\nInch\n1\ncontracts for\nadvertising running continuously:\n16.00 to 115.00,\ndiscount\n20\npercent.\n16.00 to 40,00 25\n40.00 to 75.00, -*0\nT6.00orover, 33\u00bb\nAverage weekly circulation, l,600copies.\nFor convenience, a full year of 52\nwill\nweeks\nbe allowed at 50 insertions, thus:\nBATS. DISC'T. NET.\nyear\u201450\nin. 17.60 II-BO i6-00\n3 loom.\n15.00 8.25 11.25\n150 in. 22.50 6.62 16.88\n4 200 in. 80.00 7.50 22.50\n6 250 in. 87.60 9.88 28.12\n6 300 ID. 45.00 18.60 81.50\n10 (Hcol.) 600 iri. 76.00 26.00 60.00\nA Paris newspaper figures out\nthat American girlls and their fam\nilies have expended nine hundred\nmillions of dollars in the purchase\nof foreign titles.\nThe deer hunting mania has cost\nthe lives of thirty Wisconsin hunters\nin half as many days, the season not\nopening there until November 11th.\nFootball is as harmless as lawn ten\nnis compared with deer hunting.\nTomorrow will be a good day to\n\"count your mercies,\" and to help\nalong the return of prosperity by\ncutting out forebodings of hard\ntimes. It will be money in your\npocket, to say nothing of health to\nyour bones, to be an optimist and a\npatriot.\nJames J. Hill, chairman of the\nboard of directors of the Great\nNorthern, says in the annual report\nof that company, just out, that the\nrate reductions granted by his line\nin the Northwest have cut earnings\n'for the year $1, 00,000. Still the\nGreat Northern had a successful\nyear, earning $55,144,402.20, an in\ncrease of 7.54 per cent.\nThe death of the veteran Winona\neditor, Daniel Sinclair, removes a\nman with an interesting history. A\nScotchman by birth, he came to\nPennsylvania as a youth, learned\nthe printer's trade and secured a\nfair education, and has been an\ninfluential editor for fifty years.\nFor forty-five years he controlled\nand edited the Winona Republican,\nand during twenty-five years of that\ntime was postmaster of that city.\nHe was active in all movements for\nthe betterment of his adopted city,\nand was especially prominent in\nwork for the park system of Winona.\nFor the past six years he has been\ntoo much of an invalid to deyote\nmuch time to newspaper work or\npolitics, but he was loyal in his\nfriendships, political or othewise,\nefr\nv.\nA *Y\nV\n4\nThe reason is that at a period when a girl's\ndigestion is weak,\nScott's Emulsion.\n\u00ab3\u00bb provides her with powerful nourishment in\ndigested form.\nIt is a food that builds and keeps up\nand J. A. Schmahl, formerly of THE\nGAZETTE, was especially proud of\nthe loyalty and interest shown by\nhim in the political campaign which\nresulted in the nomination and elec\ntion of Mr. Schmahl to the office of\nSecretary of State,\nThere are just two political idols\nin this -country\u2014Theodore Roosevelt\nand William Jennings Bryan, ob\nserves the Duluth News-Tribune.\nThe'financiers can take [their choice.\nBut next November it will be either\nthe man who has Roosevelt's en\ndorsement or it will be Bryan who\nwill be his successor. In either\nevent it will be such an endorse\nment of the President and his poli\ncies as will possibly convince the\nfinanciers that they must be at\nleast decidedly honest and fair or\ntake the consequences.\nAmong things to be thankful for\nto-morrow, are the many favorable\nweather indications pointed out by\nthe weather-wise: Ducks have been\nin no haste to migrate. Beavers,\nlike the butterfly, are enjoying\nthemselves, taking no thought of\nwhat may eome in form of cold\nweather. The possum's attitude is\nthat *of an animal which does not\nlook for heavy snows, and zero\nwinter. Fish worms are near the\nsurface of.the ground- Chickens\nhave not added to their feathers an\nunderskirt of down. The goosebone\nis calm and clean. Thus nature re\nveals to the sons of men glad tidings\nof great joy. The winter will be\nmild. Let us be duly grateful. It\nis a thrilling message. Like the\npoor the weather prophet is always\nwith us and let his light shine.\nSometimes he hits and sometimes he\nmisses, but either way it is just as\nwell to lay in a good supply of coal.\nA canvass of a score of prominent\nRepublicans and Democrats of Red\nwood Falls, in the interest of a lead\ning daily, made the past week,\nevolved the fact that about three\nfourths of these citizens want Roose\nvelt as first choice for president.\nThe second choice of the same par\nties is significant in being for men\nmore or less of the'Roosevelt stamp,\nDemocrats generally naming Bryan\nor Folk as first or second choice, and\nRepublicans Taft, Hughes or LaFol\nlet. The surprising fact was that\nfully half or the Democrats went on\nrecord as favoring a Republican\u2014\nRoosevelt\u2014for next president. These\nwere generally business men who\nare a little skeptical about Bryan\n\u2014who is the admitted coming man\non the Democratic presidential hori\nzon\u2014being quite safe along financial\nlines, though all admit the honesty\nof his purpose in a general way. If\nRedwood Falls sentiment is repre\nsentative of the state and nation,\nthe next president will either be\nRoosevelt or some one with the\nRoosevelt ideas as to a square deal\nfor the common people as well as\nfor the capitalist. The politician\nwho wins next year will have to give\nconvincing testimony that he is hon\nest, regardless of whether he is\na good party man or not.\nGirlhood and Scot-fs Emulsion are\nlinked together.\nThe girl who takes Scoff's\nsion has plenty of rich, red blood she is\nplump, active and energetic*\n'trengUv v. Mr V\n\u00ab8\u00bb' itUVeX V\nALL DRUGGISTS I 60e. AND $1.00.\n\u00ab9\ne\ni\n0. B. Turrell Writes of Conditions\nRedwood People Around Ryder.\ncomfortablv.\nThe season has opened very late\nand cold and seeding was so far de\nlayed that the crop has not been as\nlarge as was hoped. With late seed\ning and dry weather the farmers\nwere disappointed with results. This\nTo have success the land must be\nin the hands of those who pay\ntaxes. Taxes and the power to en\nforce them pretty nearly represent\nthe government, and until that con\ndition in the development of a new\ncommunity is reached it cannot be\nsaid to be fully organized.\nMr. W. E. Baker and myself are\nthe only Redwood representatives\nhere. Minot and DesLacs together\nhave quite a number of Redwood\nmen.\nMr. Baker has just returned from\nMondak, Montana, where he looked\nover the government irrigation pro\nject now under construction. Ac\ncording to Mr. Baker the water is\ntaken from the Yellowstone river\nnear Glendive, where the govern\nment has put in a dam 8 feet above\nhigh water mark and a ditch 70\nmiles long is being dug along the\nriver bottom and provides water for\n60,000 acres of the bottom land.\nThe government will charge up\nthe total expense against the land\nholders to pay in ten annual pay\nments without interest.\nThe cost of water is not yet known\nbut is supposed to be from three to\nfour dollars an acre a year for the\nten years. After that time it is to\nbe free. It is admitted that with\nsufficient water these lands will be\ncome very productive, but they\nshould be, to make them desirable\nas an investment.\nThe present owners of the land\nask from $20 to $30 per acre, and\nmany want to sell. At say $4000\nfor 160 acres (only a quarter section\ncan be held by one party) and four\ndollars an acre for ten years for\nwater the prospective buyer must\nhave a lot of faith to go into the\nscheme to raise ordinary farm crops.\nThere are many ways though, with\nout raising wheat. Alfalfa, sugar\nbeets and other industries may\ntake up the land and make it profit\nable.\nWe are giving very fine fall\nweather. 0. B. TURRELL.\nEddy and the Drink Habit\nThe highest peak in the Entire\nrange of folly is the senseless and\nsupremely silly custom of treating.\nThis custom is the true dementia\nAmericanna.\nIf itrwere notlfor the respectable\ndrinking the^disreputable drinking\nwould soon be abolished.\nThere*is no[difference between the\nman before the bar and the man be\nhind the bar except that the man\nbefore the bar'is the bigger chump.\nThe saloon business is the only\none in the\" world for which screens\najre put up to conceal the amount of\nbusiness done and the character of\nthe patrons.\nWhat can exceed' in foolishness\nthe deliberate act of paying out\ngood |money for the acquisition of\ndangerous disease and horrible vices.\nThe third number of the course\nwill be Parlette, the star attraction\nof last year, Thursday, Dec. 5th.\n4\nWk#| V.\"\nHarrowing Experiences of Mrs. Tarbell\nas Captive of Little Crow.\nTo THE GAZETTE When I left All this occurred in a few minutes,\nRedwood I did not think so long a\nkut\nto\ntime would pass before I made a! seemed to last for hours.' In agony\nreport to THE GAZETTE, It is six'and despair I awaited my turn to\nmonths today that I set up house- suffer, offering an earnest prayer\nkeeping in my shack a mile out of that death to myself and little ones\nRyder. The time had passed pleas- might come speedily. An Indian\nantly and I am now within two running toward us. I thought\nmonths of the end of my residence my time had come. Putting an arm\nof eight months necessary to make i about each of my little ones I wished\ncommuted proof on a homestead.\nthat\nOf the next two months I have a i that\nis my fourth year in this vicinity you and your children to my tepee,\nand is the first I have known with- and then you will be my squaw. All\nout sufficient rainfall during the\ngrowing season. As it is, the coun\ntry is getting along nicely with\nabout half a crop, the high prices\nhaving done much to make up the\nshortage. There has been a large\nacreage of new breaking during the\nsummer, and this section goes into\nwinter ready to put in a much larger\ncrop next spring than heretofore.\nThe claims in this part of the\nstate are being proved up very fast\nand the land is passing into the\nhands of private owner?. Until this\nis done the towns, counties and\nschool districts have to get along in\na haphazard way.\nus women and children it\nI could provoke the red fiend so\nhe\nlittle misgiving as winter is ap-1his reaching me I was astonished to\nproahing but think I will get along\nwould kill us outright. On\nhear him\nsPeak\nin\nreal friendly\ntones. He shook hands with me,\nbut retained his grasp and soon re\nmoved my rings.\nI said: \"Are you going to kill\nme?\" He answered \"No, the medi\ncine man says he must not kill you,\nHe says I must save you and take\nthe nice women we will not kill:\nthey will be squaws for the Indian\nbraves.\"\nThere were 27 in our party when\nwe started, and eight were killed by\nthe Indians when they overtook us.\nI may here state that more than 800\nwhites were killed by the savages\nwithin\na,\nfew days. Several counties\nin the western part of the state\nwere depopulated and thousands of\npersons became fugitives and were\nleft destitute without food or shel\nter.\nMrs. David Carrothers and her\nbaby Mrs. Earle and two daughters\naged 13 and 7 Mrs. N. D. White\nand baby daughter, and myself and\nmy two children, a little daughter,\nAlthea, aged 4, and a little son,\nThomas W., of 2 years, were put in\nto two wagons by our captors and\nour journey into captivity began.\nThe most of the men and boys es\ncaped by flight.\nWe were started for Little Crow's\nvillage, on the south side of the\nMinnesota, two miles west of the\nLower Agency. On reaching Mr.\nEarle's house the Indians halted,\ntook from the house everything they\nwanted and broke up ^everything\nelse, shooting the pigs and chickens.\nThe same destruction was visited\nupon every other white settler's\nhouse that we passed.\nAfter we had proceeded some dis\ntace we left the main road and start\ned to cross the Minnesota river at\na\nford. While crossing the river one\nof the whiffle-trees of the wagon in\nwhich I rode became entangled in a\nwheel and I was ordered to unfasten\nit. I easily did so, but had to stand\nin the stream while at work and got\nwet to my waist. I was then ord\nered and compelled to drive as fast\nas possible. When we reached the\ncrest of the bluff on the south side\nof the river the wagon containing\nMrs. David Carrothers and child,\nMisses Julia Earle and Julia White\nseparated from us and drove away\ntowards Shakopee's village:\nWe reached Little Crow's camp\nabout 3 o'clock in the afternoon, and\nhalted about 40 rods from the chief's\nhouse. I was then ordered to un\nhitch the horses and go into a corn\nfield and bring some corn to feed\nthem. The Indian warriors and\ntheir squaws were coming into camp\nfrom every direction, the squaws\nladen with plunder, the men with\nbloody scalps of their butchered vic\ntims at their belts. A great many\nwhite women and girls were brought\nin as captives.\nAbout five o'clock Little Crow\ncame over to see me and I asked him\nif I could go either to his house or\nto the medicine man's tepee. I had\npreviously asked the leader of the\nIndians who, captured me to let me\ngo to Little Crow's house, but he\nhad angrily refused me, saying that\nI belonged to him. Little Crow\ntold me that the medicine man had\ngone with the warriors to attack\nFort Ridgley, but that I might go\nwith him so, with my children, I\naccompanied him to his house.\nWhen we reached the chief's\nhouse I told him I was hungry and\nthat my children had had nothing\n\u00bbt'\nJ:\n1\nIs\nss-\nPHONE 30\nto\neat all day. I had always fed him\nwhen he came to my house and I\nexpected him to do the same by me.\nHe became very cross. Pointing to\na sack of flour he said: \"There is\nflour: if you are hungry, make your\nself some bread,\" and theft he left\nthe house. One of his squaws came\nin and I told her that the poor chil\ndren were very hungry, and she\nmade us some coffee and bread.\nShe\ntold me that there were many white\nwomen captives and that they mad\"'\nContinued on Sixth Page\n\u2022t l-\ntfttTOKEfOOD\n\\\\Notee or \"Water\nV stjostupr cnrsTtfts\nNo (.hernias\n.'-.a?.\nPw\u00abTv4Uvt.\nV.UMd\nHtiural TUvor\nI\ni# (Xu*\\uy\nWHICH \u2014fresh, clean, wholesome oysters with a.\ndelicate salt-water tang, the true flavor\nof sea\u2014the Sealshipt kind\nor\nflarbby, slimy, bruised, white oysters,'\ntasting of little else than stale water and\npreservatives\u2014the tub kind.\nWHICH in a word appeals to you as the more\npalatable, appetizing and sanitary,\nSEALSHIPT OYSTERS\nOR\nTHE TUB KIND\nDo not forget oar\nHome Made Bread, Pies and Cookies.\nW. J. SMITHERS\nWhen the frost is on the pumpkin\nAnd the rigors of winter threaten, your grocer\ncan help by supplying wholesome provisions for\nwinter appetites at moderate cost. Look over our\nfall stock of staple groceries and save money by\nbuying in quantities.\nChoice fruits and vegetables, home grown and\nimported.\nTry our Coffees and Teas.\nRemember* we pay CASH for CREAM and EGGS\nH. F. BUECHNER\nIT'S UP TO YOU\nWho appreciate right GROCERIES at right prices\nto order them where you can get them that w ay.\nIt's up to us to stand back of our goods and that\nwhich we say of them.\nFRUIT JARS\u2014in pint, quart and 2-quart sizes. Let us\nshow you the new Schram Automatic Sealing kind,\nCOMMON TUMBLERS\u20142 for 5c, or 30c per dozen.\nNEW TEAS\u2014LOCOMOTIVE brand is the best.\nA HANDSOME DISH\u2014given away with each pound\nof Crown Blend Coffee.\nPRETTY JELLY MOLDS-one given with every three\npackages of jeilvcon. Come six in a set.\nJ. M. Dunnington\nII\n500 bushel\nCorn Cribs\n$4.50\nE. A. PEASE\n1\n1\nr)\nI\ny\\","height":"25587","width":"17745"}}
